Question 1

We will use the dataset riskfactors available in the class data link.

There are two files holding the same data. riskfactors.rds stores the data in R-native format, which can be read as riskfactors <- readRDS('data/riskfactors.rds') (you can update the path based on where you store the file). The riskfactors.csv file can be read using read_csv.

riskfactors <- readRDS('data/riskfactors.rds')

Question 2

Plot the frequency distribution of marital status in this dataset, as seen below.

ggplot(riskfactors %>% filter(!is.na(marital)), aes(fct_rev(fct_infreq(marital))))+
  geom_bar() + 
  labs(x = 'Marital status', 
       y = 'Frequency',
       title = 'Frequency distribution of marital status')+
  coord_flip()

Important points for this plot.

  1. I do not want a bar for missing values
  2. The tricky part may be getting the right order. See the forcats cheatsheet for hints
  3. There is use of coord_flip. This should be the last thing you do in the ggplot pipe.
plot_data <- riskfactors %>% filter(is.na(marital))

ggplot(plot_data, 
       aes(x = fct_rev(fct_infreq(marital))))+
  geom_bar() + 
  labs(x = 'Marital status', 
       y = 'Frequency',
       title = 'Frequency distribution of marital status')+
  coord_flip()

library(ggrepel)
USArrests %>% rownames_to_column('State') %>%

Question 4

Using the riskfactors data, create a panel of plots using any of the three packages introduced in lecture, where the plots will be

  1. A histogram of age
  2. A frequency bar plot of sex
  3. A boxplot of BMI by education level
  4. A barplot showing the proportion of each educational level for each marital status.
library(ggplot2)
library(cowplot)
library(ggpubr)
library(patchwork)

plt1 <- ggplot(riskfactors) + geom_histogram(aes(x=age))
plt2 <- ggplot(riskfactors) + geom_bar(aes(x = sex))
plt3 <- ggplot(riskfactors) + geom_boxplot(aes(x = education, y = bmi))
plt4 <- ggplot(riskfactors) + 
  geom_bar(aes(x = marital, fill = education), position='fill')+
  coord_flip()

Extra credit (10 pts)

Install the coronavirus package (install.packages('coronavirus')). Once that is installed, run coronavirus::update_dataset(). This will update the data to the latest data from JHU, and also ask you to restart your R session (Session > Restart R).

Part a

The coronavirus dataset is in the coronavirus package and contains data on cases, deaths and recoveries on a daily basis from around the world. We will only use the deaths data, which is obtained by filtering the rows of the coronavirus dataset to contain only rows with type=="death"

Extract out data for 6th July, 2020 (date == "2020-07-06) and then identify the top 10 countries in terms of deaths on that date.

library(coronavirus)
countries_10 <- coronavirus %>% 
  filter(type=='death') %>% 
  filter(date=='2020-07-06') %>% 
  group_by(country) %>% 
  summarise(cases = sum(cases, na.rm=T)) %>% 
  ungroup() %>% 
  slice_max(cases, n=10) %>% 
  pull(country)

There are a couple of nuances here. For some countries, there is also provincial data, so you have to sum over those rows within country (%>% group_by(country) %>% summarise(cases = sum(cases, na.rm=T) %>% ungroup()))

You can use slice_max to grab the approriate rows. To pull out the countries, you can then use %>% pull(country) and save the result. You should have

##  [1] "Brazil"       "Mexico"       "India"        "US"           "Peru"        
##  [6] "Iran"         "Russia"       "Colombia"     "South Africa" "Iraq"

Part b

Make a plot of smoothed lines of daily deaths over time for these 10 countries, from the beginning of the data collection to 6th July. Transform the country variable so that the legend is ordered in order of deaths on 6th July. The y-axis should also be log-transformed (scale_y_log10()). This should look something like this.

library(coronavirus)
coronavirus %>% filter(date==max(date), type=='death') %>% group_by(country) %>% summarise(cases = sum(cases, na.rm=T)) %>% ungroup() %>% slice_max(cases, n=10) %>% pull(country) -> country_top10

coronavirus %>% filter(type=='death', country %in% country_top10, date <= '2020-07-06') %>% 
  ggplot(aes(x = date, y = cases, 
             color = fct_reorder2(country, date, cases)))+
  geom_smooth(se=FALSE) + 
  scale_y_log10('Number of deaths') +
  labs(x = '', color = 'Country',
       title = 'Patterns of daily deaths globally from COVID-19',
       caption = 'Johns Hopkins University CCSE, 2020')
